{I have been familiar with Alekhine's Defense for 20 years (almost since birth). Since then, thousands of games have been played. There is not a single top player who has not been burned at least once by the hot walls of this defense. When you often play a variation, your opponents will definitely prepare against you. Once, while participating in a tournament, my coach and I decided that this time, I would play 1...c5 ; we spent many hours on preparation and analysis. The Play Day came, we shook hands, and the opponent moved e4 , to which I immediately took my knight and put it on f6 !  My coach was just shocked. I played Alekhine's Defense too often, so my hand immediately reached the right place. Luckily, I managed to win. Since then, my skill in this variation has only grown, and I want to share my experience and ideas with you. I hope this defense will help you achieve your goals and bring you many victories! Many years ago, back in the days when humans could beat computers, I played against Chessmaster5000. I played with white. e4 , and he answers with Nf6! I was already thinking about resignation, but I decided to make a couple more moves: e5 Nd5 d4 d6 Nf3 dxe5 Nxe5 c6 c4 , expecting that the computer would retreat the knight, but it jumped to b4 with Nb4 , which was a surprise for me - what kind of stupidity is this? Why can't I just attack it with a pawn? So I moved a3 , and then, like a bolt from the blue, it played Qxd4!! Then, everything became clear to me. I did not continue the battle because if I captured the queen, his knight would go to c2 and make a fork, thereby leaving him with an extra pawn; after this lesson, I began to use these options myself and have already caught a lot of strong grandmasters in this trap. By the way, the last one whom I tricked today.} 1. Z0 *


