1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. exd6 {The immediate trade on d6 does not cause us any problems whatsoever.} cxd6 6. Be3 Nc6 7. Qd2 Qa5 {Activating the queen and slowing down White's development by preventing O-O-O .} 8. Nf3 a6 {Covering the b5 -square and hinting at an eventual queenside expansion with ... b7 - b5 .} 9. Be2 Bf5 10. O-O e5 {Building the standard pawn chain in the center and taking away the d4 -square from White's knight.} 11. Nh4 Be6 12. f4 Be7 {Ignoring the nonexistant threats on the kingside and completing our development and hitting the knight.} *


