1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 a6 {Forcing White's hand. We are almost never opposed to Bxc6 +, which gives us the bishop pair and dynamic prospects in the center.} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. O-O e6 {Opening up the e7 -square for our bishop, and preparing to undermine White's central control with ... f6 .} 9. Bg5 Be7 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Re1 c5 {A strong positional move, taking the d4 -square under control and preparing to fianchetto our bishop on the long diagonal.} 12. Qd3 O-O 13. Rad1 Rd8 {Guarding the d6 -pawn.} 14. c4 Bb7 {We possess a powerful bishop and a solid pawn structure.} *

