1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 ({Along with} 4. Nf3 {, this is the most popular continuation. White kicks away the knight and occupies more central space.}) 4... Nb6 5. exd6 ({The main alternative to this move,} 5. f4 {, is known as The Four Pawns Attack and is examined in its own chapter.}) (5. Nf3 {is the only feasible alternative to f4 and exd6 , and it will likely transpose to the main line since White can hardly keep the central tension up for long.} Bg4 6. exd6 exd6 7. Be2 Be7 8. O-O O-O {will transpose to exd6 exd6 Nf3 Be7 Be2 O-O O-O Bg4 .}) 5... exd6 {White does not have that many developmental setups. Essentially, there are two methods of development: those involving bringing the knight to f3 , and those involving developing the knight to e2 . While there are nominally a lot of options in this position, most of them ultimately transpose into the same type of position once White commits to developing the g1 -knight.} 6. h3 ({One of the most common alternatives to} 6. Nf3 {and Nc3 . White prevents ... Bg4 in preparation for developing the knight.}) 6... Be7 {Our plans do not change; we make this move in response to almost all of White's options. The first priority is to complete our kingside development.} 7. Nf3 O-O {Completing the Kingside development.} 8. Nc3 Re8 {Occupying the open file and x-raying the king. We threaten the nasty check on g5 , forcing White to develop the bishop to a more passive square on e2 .} 9. Be2 Bf6 {Deploying the bishop to its standard ideal square.} 10. O-O Nc6 11. Be3 Bf5 {Using the fact that White's light-squared bishop is on an inferior square to develop as actively as possible.} 12. Rc1 h6 {A familiar and important prophylactic move, ensuring that the common trick g4 - g5 will not trap our dark-squared bishop once a knight lands on e7 .} 13. b3 d5 {Having made all the necessary preparations, it is time for the central strike.} 14. c5 Nc8 {As usual, the knight is rerouted to the center via c8 and e7 .} 15. a3 N8e7 16. b4 a6 {Preventing the further progress of White's Queenside pawns.} 17. Qd2 Be4 {Centralizing the bishop and applying indirect pressure on the d4 -pawn, as well as vacating the f5 -square for our knight.} 18. Rfd1 Nf5 {The pressure against White's center has reached a peak, and the d4 -pawn is very likely to fall in the next few moves. Note that Nxe4 is always strongly met by recapturing with the pawn, sending away the f3 -knight and picking off the d4 -pawn.} *


