1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 ({Along with} 4. Nf3 {, this is the most popular continuation. White kicks away the knight and occupies more central space.}) 4... Nb6 5. exd6 ({The main alternative to this move,} 5. f4 {, is known as the four pawns attack and is examined in its own chapter. Nf3 is the only feasible alternative to f4 and exd6 , and it will likely transpose to the main line since White can hardly keep the central tension up for long. Bg4 exd6 exd6 Be2 Be7 O-O O-O transposes to exd6 exd6 Nf3 Be7 Be2 O-O O-O Bg4 .}) 5... exd6 {White does not have that many developmental setups. Essentially, there are two methods of development: those involving bringing the knight to f3 , and those involving developing the knight to e2 . While there are nominally a lot of options in this position, most of them ultimately transpose into the same type of position once White commits to developing the g1 -knight.} 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Nf3 O-O {Getting the king to safety. This is our response to all of White's seventh-move alternatives.} 8. Bd3 Bg4 {Deploying the bishop on its most active possible square.} 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3 Bf6 {Deploying the bishop and pressuring the d4 -pawn.} 11. b3 (11. h3 Bh5 {transposes to h3 Bh5 O-O Nc6 Be3 Bf6 .}) 11... Re8 {Improving the Rook.} 12. Be2 h6 {This is a very important move, which contains a deep prophylactic idea: after Black plays the typical sequence ... d5  c5 ... Nc8 , the knight can head to e7 without worrying about the tactical idea h3  Bh5  g4  Bg6  g5 . Now, the g5 -square is under control.} 13. h3 Bh5 {As usual, we do not give away the light-squared bishop under any circumstances.} 14. Qd2 d5 {It is time for the thematic central strike.} 15. c5 Nc8 {As is standard in this line, the knight is maneuvered to f5 , where it will exert tremendous pressure on White's center.} 16. Rfe1 N8e7 {Note the role of the pawn on h6 , which prevents the typical g2 - g4 - g5 break, which would otherwise trap the bishop.} 17. g4 Bg6 18. Rad1 b6 {Undermining the Queenside.} 19. cxb6 axb6 20. Bb5 Rf8 {Unpinning!} 21. h4 Qc8 {Hitting the pawn on g4 . White's Kingside falls apart entirely.} *

