1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 ({Along with} 4. Nf3 {, this is the most popular continuation. White kicks away the knight and occupies more central space.}) 4... Nb6 5. exd6 ({The main alternative to this move,} 5. f4 {, is known as the four pawns attack and is examined in its own chapter. Nf3 is the only feasible alternative to f4 and exd6 , and it will likely transpose to the main line since White can hardly keep the central tension up for long. Bg4 exd6 exd6 Be2 Be7 O-O O-O transposes to exd6 exd6 Nf3 Be7 Be2 O-O O-O Bg4 .}) 5... exd6 {White does not have that many developmental setups. Essentially, there are two methods of development: those involving bringing the knight to f3 , and those involving developing the knight to e2 . While there are nominally a lot of options in this position, most of them ultimately transpose into the same type of position once White commits to developing the g1 -knight.} 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Nge2 c6 {This move represents the central idea of the line. We are preparing to stake our claim in the center with ... d5 . As for the knight on b8 , it can join society via a6 and c7 . When White places the Knight on e2 , Black doesn't have a good spot for the bishop because, after ... Bg4 , White will have f3 ! This is why we changed our strategy in this game.} 9. O-O Na6 {Developing the knight, and hinting at ... Nb4 in addition to ... Nc7 .} 10. a3 {This is the most straightforward way to prevent ... Nb4 .} d5 {Having completed the development of our knights, it is time for the traditional central strike, which we prepared with the move ... c6 .} 11. c5 Nd7 12. Qc2 g6 {Blunting the battery.} 13. f4 {White attempts to crash through on the Kingside with f5 , but we are just in time to thwart his bloodthirsty designs.} f5 {Meeting fire with fire! Not only does this prevent f5 , but it also establishes a massive stronghold on e4 .} 14. g4 Nf6 {A powerful sacrifice, forcing White to open up his own king and ultimately preparing to access the outpost on e4 .} 15. gxf5 gxf5 16. Bxf5 Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Qc8 {Getting rid of White's most active piece.} 18. Qxc8 Raxc8 19. f5 Nh5 {Our compensation for the pawn is excellent: White's king is compromised, the f5 -pawn is weak, and we can continue improving our position in a variety of ways, i.e. ... Bf6 , ... Rfe8 , while the knight can drop back to g7 and hit the f5 -pawn at the right moment} *


