1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. dxe5 Bg4 {Developing the bishop to its most active square, and preparing to apply pressure on the weak e5 -pawn.} 6. Be2 Nc6 {Now that the bishop has committed to e2 , we do not fear Bb5 and can develop the knight to its most active square.} 7. O-O e6 8. c4 {Pressuring the c4 -pawn, creating the potential threat of ... Bxf3 followed by ... Nxc4 . In positions with the weak White pawn on e5 , the trade of queens is almost always in Black's favor.} Nb6 9. b3 Qxd1 {As usual, we are more than happy to swap queens, as it makes it far easier to attack the e5 -pawn.} 10. Rxd1 Nd7 {The typical retreat; the knights combine forces to attack e5 .} 11. Bb2 O-O-O 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Ndxe5 {White has zero compensation for the lost pawn.} *

