1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. c4 {A rare, but dangerous line, which forces Black to respond accurately. It is very important to avoid the automatic retreat. Rather, we fight fire with fire, advancing our e-pawn and counterattack our knight.} e4 6. cxd5 exf3 7. Qxf3 {As a result of the trade, White has doubled d-pawns, but they hamper the active development of our Queenside. Instead, we begin by developing our dark-squared bishop, and, when the time is right, chip away at White's center with ... c7 - c6 .} g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 {Fianchettoing the bishop and hitting the pawn on d4 . In most cases, we choose to develop our pieces rather than wasting a tempo on the capture of the pawn.} 9. Bf4 c6 {The thematic move, undermining the d5 -pawn to guarantee freer Queenside development.} 10. Bc4 O-O 11. O-O cxd5 12. Bxd5 Nc6 {Just as in the 8. Bc4 variation, we are ready to offer up the pawn in exchange for the bishop pair and superior prospects for our light-squared bishop.} 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qxc6 Bg4 {Connecting our heavy pieces, and bringing out the bishop to an active post, preventing White from increasing their control over the d-pawn with Rad1 .} 15. d5 Rc8 {Mobilizing the Rook and harrassing White's queen.} 16. Qb5 a6 {A savvy shot, undermining White's control over the d5 -pawn.} 17. Qxa6 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Qxd5 {White's extra pawn is meaningless: our superior piece activity, coupled with the long-term weakness of White's Queenside pawns, guarantees Black an easy game.} *


