1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Be2 Bf5 {When possible, this is the ideal development square for the bishop.} 7. O-O Nd7 {Natural and strong, developing our knight and smoking out White's knight from the center.} 8. Nf3 e6 9. c4 N5f6 {In this particular instance, this move is preferrable to ... Nb4 . We need the knight on the Kingside in order to make the ... e6 - e5 break easier to achieve later on.} 10. Bf4 Be7 11. Nc3 O-O {Completing our Kingside development.} 12. Bd3 {As usual, there is nothing to fear from this trade.} Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Qa5 {Activating the queen and opening up the d8 -square for the Rook.} 14. Rfe1 Rfd8 15. a3 Nf8 {Retooling the knight to the Kingside, in order to increase our pressure on d4 .} 16. b4 Qh5 {Shuttling the queen over to the safest square on the board.} 17. Bg3 Ng6 18. Rad1 a6 {Preparing to carve out the d5 -square with ... b5 . Note that a4 hangs the b4 -pawn, so White has no satisfactory answer.} *

