1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 {This is the most principled continuation for White.} dxe5 6. fxe5 Bf5 ({In my experience, this move complicates the position for white. It is less common than} 6... Nc6 {, and faces White with immediate practical difficulties. The main point is to delay ... Nc6 , to have the option of challenging White's center with ... c5 later on.}) 7. Nc3 e6 8. Be3 Bb4 {This presents White with a huge menu of options, complicating his experience. Based on my experience, White has a very hard time finding a proper arrangement of pieces, and it is easy to commit a serious error as early as the next move.} 9. Nf3 c5 {The typical move, shattering White's center.} 10. a3 {A popular move that is frequently played at the highest level.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qh4+ {A strong, forcing line, posing serious practical problems.} 12. g3 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qe4 {A double attack, forcing White to unfavorably exchange queens.} 14. Qf3 Qxf3 15. Nxf3 O-O {Black is obviously better due to White's horrific pawn structure.} *

