1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight. In certain positions, we transpose to the e4 e5 Nf3} Nf6 {Nxe5 d6} 4. Nf3 Ne4 5. Nc3 {variation of Petrov's Game.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Bc4 {Obviously, we cannot capture on e5 due to f7 . Instead, we focus on rapid and active development.} Nc6 6. exd6 Qxd6 {The queen trade is in our favor, since White's damaged pawn structure will be a weightier factor in the endgame.} 7. Qe2 e5 {Claiming the center. The pawn on e5 is well-defended by the queen and knight.} 8. Nf3 Be6 ({Developing the bishop and preparing to castle Queenside. Note that} 8... Bg4 {falls prey to the classic trick} 9. Bxf7+ {, so it is important to challenge White's only active piece.}) 9. O-O Bxc4 10. Qxc4 f6 {Removing the pawn on f6 from the purview of White's queen. We are now ready to castle Queenside and solidify our control over the d-file.} 11. Be3 O-O-O 12. b4 Qd5 {Once again, we use the queen trade as a powerful defensive weapon. In order to keep the ladies on the board, White must consign his queen to a more passive square.} 13. Qe2 Be7 {Completing our development.} 14. a4 f5 {The position remains double-edged. We have major pawn pressure in the center, with threats of ... f5 - f4 and ... e5 - e4 . If White pushes b5 , we will establish our knight on the fine blockading square a5 .} *

