1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight. In certain positions, we transpose to the e4 e5 Nf3} Nf6 {Nxe5 d6} 4. Nf3 Ne4 5. Nc3 {variation of Petrov's Game.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Bc4 {Obviously, we cannot capture on e5 due to f7 . Instead, we focus on rapid and active development.} Nc6 6. Nf3 dxe5 {Now that the queen is protected, Bxf7 + is no longer possible.} 7. Qe2 {An enterprising sacrifice, but with accurate play, we are able to keep the pawn and diffuse White's initiative.} f6 {Defending the pawn.} 8. Be3 e6 {An important move, cutting out the influence of White's light-squared bishop and opening up more breathing room for our queen and minor pieces.} 9. Nd2 {This difficult move is the only way to keep objectively sufficient compensation.} Bd6 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Ne4 f5 {Forcing White's hand.} 12. Nxd6 cxd6 13. f4 Qc7 {Removing the queen from the pin, and solidifying our pawn phalanx in the center.} 14. fxe5 Na5 {A very important intermezzo, opening up an attack on the light-squared bishop and taking the c5 -square under control.} 15. Bb5 dxe5 {Now that Bc5 is no longer possible, we can recapture the pawn.} 16. Rhf1 a6 {Sending away White's bishop to a more passive square, making it possible for us to complete our development.} 17. Bd3 Bd7 {White has enough compensation for the pawn, but not more than that. We have many ways to improve our position, such as ... b5 and ... Nc4 . White has no easy way to continue pressuring the center.} *

