1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight. In certain positions, we transpose to the e4 e5 Nf3} Nf6 {Nxe5 d6} 4. Nf3 Ne4 5. Nc3 {variation of Petrov's Game.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Bc4 {Obviously, we cannot capture on e5 due to f7 . Instead, we focus on rapid and active development.} Nc6 6. Nf3 dxe5 {Now that the queen is protected, Bxf7 + is no longer possible.} 7. Qe2 {An enterprising sacrifice, but with accurate play, we are able to keep the pawn and diffuse White's initiative.} f6 {Defending the pawn.} 8. Be3 e6 {An important move, cutting out the influence of White's light-squared bishop and opening up more breathing room for our queen and minor pieces.} 9. Nd2 {This difficult move is the only way to keep objectively sufficient compensation.} Bd6 10. O-O-O O-O 11. g4 Ne7 {A lovely maneuver, bringing the knigght to the excellent d5 -square. We are more than happy to give back our extra pawn in order to generate active prospects for our pieces.} 12. Ne4 Nd5 13. Rhg1 Nxe3 {Seizing the bishop pair.} 14. Qxe3 Qe7 {Removing the queen from the pin and solidifying the e6 -pawn. We will follow up by completing our development with ... Bd7 . Obviously, g5 will always be met with ... f5 .} *


