1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight. In certain positions, we transpose to the e4 e5 Nf3} Nf6 {Nxe5 d6} 4. Nf3 Ne4 5. Nc3 {variation of Petrov's Game.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Bc4 {Obviously, we cannot capture on e5 due to f7 . Instead, we focus on rapid and active development.} Nc6 6. Nf3 dxe5 {Now that the queen is protected, Bxf7 + is no longer possible.} 7. Qxd8+ Nxd8 8. Nxe5 f6 {Kicking away White's knight, and preparing to establish a well-defended pawn chain in the center. Black is better due to our superior central control and White's ruined pawn structure.} 9. Nd3 e5 10. Be3 Be6 {Trading, or kicking away, White's only active piece.} 11. Bb5+ c6 12. Ba4 a5 {A pretty move, expanding on the Queenside and creating the potential threat of ... b5 and ... a4 .} 13. O-O-O Bxa2 {Why not? Because of our previous move, White cannot trap and win the bishop due to ... b5 .} 14. b3 b5 15. Kb2 bxa4 16. Kxa2 axb3+ 17. cxb3 Nb7 {The smoke has cleared, and White has no compensation for the pawn.} *

