1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight. In certain positions, we transpose to the e4 e5 Nf3} Nf6 {Nxe5 d6} 4. Nf3 Ne4 5. Nc3 {variation of Petrov's Game.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Bf4 Nc6 {Developing and applying pressure to the e5 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 dxe5 {Once again, we are not opposed to the queen trade,and will easily rebuild active development with a few active moves.} 7. Qxd8+ Nxd8 8. Bxe5 c6 {Before kicking away the bishop, we must first move the c-pawn to a defended position.} 9. O-O-O f6 {Now, we embark on the standard procedure of kicking away the piece and e5 and building the central pawn chain.} 10. Bg3 e5 11. Bc4 ({Improving the knight and refraining from the tempting Be6 , which blunders two pieces for a Rook due to} 11. Rxd8+ {.}) 11... Nf7 12. Rhe1 Be7 {Continuing to develop our minor pieces.} 13. Nd2 h5 {Expanding on the Kingside and threatening to trap the bishop.} 14. h3 h4 {Grabbing more space and driving the bishop to an even more pasive square.} 15. Bh2 Nd6 16. Bb3 g5 {An important prophylactic move, preventing the opening of the center with f2 - f4 .} *


