1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight. In certain positions, we transpose to the e4 e5 Nf3} Nf6 {Nxe5 d6} 4. Nf3 Ne4 5. Nc3 {variation of Petrov's Game.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 a6 {Forcing White's hand. We are almost never opposed to Bxc6 +, which gives us the bishop pair and dynamic prospects in the center.} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qe2 Qd7 {A powerful and nonstandard move, bringing out the queen, and protecting the c6 -pawn, taking the sting out of Qc4 .} 9. O-O f6 {An important move, undermining the e5 -pawn.} 10. exf6 gxf6 11. Nd4 e5 {Creating a well-protected pawn in the center.} 12. f4 Qg4 {One of the many points of our 8th move is revealed. The best way to challenge White's initiative is to force an endgame. If White refrains from the queen trade, we will exert tremendous pressure down the g-file with ... Rg8 .} 13. Qxg4 Bxg4 14. Nxc6 a5 {Suddenly, the knight on c6 has no way out!} 15. fxe5 fxe5 16. b4 {This is the only way to defend against the massive threat of ... Bd7 , but it opens up excellent prospects for us on the Queenside.} axb4 17. cxb4 Ra4 {Power chess! The Rook on a4 prevents White from pushing their a-pawn, and exerts long-term pressure on the b4 -pawn.} 18. a3 Be6 {We have completely paralyzed White's pieces. The knight on c6 is cut off from the rest of society, and we will pressure it with ... Bd5 . Subsequently, we will exert pressure on the Kingside with ... Rg8 .} *


