1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight. In certain positions, we transpose to the e4 e5 Nf3} Nf6 {Nxe5 d6} 4. Nf3 Ne4 5. Nc3 {variation of Petrov's Game.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 a6 {Forcing White's hand. We are almost never opposed to Bxc6 +, which gives us the bishop pair and dynamic prospects in the center.} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qe2 Qd7 {A powerful and nonstandard move, bringing out the queen, and protecting the c6 -pawn, taking the sting out of Qc4 .} 9. Be3 (9. Bf4 {see Bf4 Qd7 Qe2 .}) 9... g6 {Preparing to fianchetto the bishop.} 10. Bd4 Rg8 {We remain alert, refraining from ... Bg7 , which loses a piece to e5 - e6 .} 11. O-O-O c5 {The point of this pawn sacrifice is to open up the e8 - a4 diagonal for our queen, which will enable us to force a queen trade.} 12. Bxc5 Qb5 {The bishop is now hanging, so White has no choice but to acquiesce to the trade and give us the a-file.} 13. Qxb5+ axb5 14. exd6 cxd6 15. Ba3 Be6 {Black's compensation for the pawn is excellent, coming in the form of the bishop pair, a superior pawn structure, and long-lasting pressure on the Queenside.} *


