1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight. In certain positions, we transpose to the e4 e5 Nf3} Nf6 {Nxe5 d6} 4. Nf3 Ne4 5. Nc3 {variation of Petrov's Game.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 a6 {Forcing White's hand. We are almost never opposed to Bxc6 +, which gives us the bishop pair and dynamic prospects in the center.} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Bf4 Qd7 {As in the Qe2 line, we deploy our queen, seizing control of the c8 - h3 and diagonal and preparing, in some cases, to bring the queen out to f5 or e6 (after a preliminary trade on f6 ).} 9. Qe2 f6 10. O-O-O Qg4 {Removing the queen from the pin with tempo. The position is exceedingly complicated, but with a series of accurate moves we are able to diffuse White's initiative and pose serious practical problems.} 11. Qe4 Bd7 {Protecting the c6 -pawn.} 12. exd6 cxd6 13. Rxd6 e5 {A powerful move, moving up the pawn and creating a sudden double-attack against the bishop on f4 and Rook on d6 . White has no choice but to give up a serious amount of material.} 14. Nxe5 fxe5 15. Qxe5+ Kf7 {The king is surprisingly safe on f7 , with the bishop and queen guarding the key e6 and f5 -squares.} 16. Rd4 c5 {Chasing away the Rook.} 17. Qd5+ Be6 {Obviously, we do not fear Qxa8 due to ... cxd4 , when the hanging bishop on f4 will signal the immediate end of White's initiative.} 18. Qb7+ Be7 19. Re4 Rad8 {Moving the Rook into position, and preparing to kick away White's queen with ... Rd7 . Objectively, the position is about equal, but it is very difficult for White to conduct his initiative accurately.} *

