1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight. In certain positions, we transpose to the e4 e5 Nf3} Nf6 {Nxe5 d6} 4. Nf3 Ne4 5. Nc3 {variation of Petrov's Game.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 a6 {Forcing White's hand. We are almost never opposed to Bxc6 +, which gives us the bishop pair and dynamic prospects in the center.} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. O-O e6 {Opening up the e7 -square for our bishop, and preparing to undermine White's central control with ... f6 .} 9. Bf4 f6 {Undermining the e5 -pawn, as is so standard in this line.} 10. exf6 Qxf6 {Recapturing with tempo, and keeping the f-file open for future use.} 11. Bg3 Be7 12. Bh4 Qf7 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Qd3 O-O {Bringing our king to safety.} 15. Rae1 Qf6 {Black has an excellent position, and the prospect of furthering our pressure in the center and on the Kingside with ... e6 - e5 , followed by the development of our bishop to f5 or g4 .} *

