1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 ({A popular alternative to} 3. d4 {, immediately challenging Black's knight. In certain positions, we transpose to the e4 e5 Nf3} Nf6 {Nxe5 d6} 4. Nf3 Ne4 5. Nc3 {variation of Petrov's Game.}) 3... Nxc3 {We are fine with the trade, since White will experience long-term problems with his pawn structure.} 4. dxc3 d6 {We undermine White's only center pawn without delay.} 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 a6 {Forcing White's hand. We are almost never opposed to Bxc6 +, which gives us the bishop pair and dynamic prospects in the center.} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. O-O e6 {Opening up the e7 -square for our bishop, and preparing to undermine White's central control with ... f6 .} 9. Qd4 f6 {This move is omnipresent across almost all of the lines in this variation. Removing the e5 -pawn enables us to develop with greater freedom, and achieve a powerful and robust pawn center.} 10. exf6 gxf6 11. Qe4 Qd7 {Once again, the queen is best positioned on this square in order to ensure the long-term safety of the c6 -pawn and to take the sting out of White's active queen.} 12. Nd4 e5 {Moving the pawn to a more well-defended square.} 13. f4 Bb7 {Developing to the long diagonal and securing the c6 -pawn. Note that the e5 -pawn is incredibly well defended.} 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Rxf6 {This incredibly tempting move turns out to be a mistake, as it grants us a devastating initiative.} O-O-O {Moving our king to safety and ignoring the pawn on e5 , which is untouchable due to ... Bg7 .} 16. Ne6 Be7 {Counter-attacking the Rook on f6 . White is horribly underdeveloped.} 17. Nxd8 Bxf6 18. Nxb7 Qd1+ {A crucial intermezzo, driving White's king out into the open and preventing the development of White's bishop.} 19. Kf2 Kxb7 {Of course, we must pick up the knight before proceeding with our initiative.} 20. Qf3 Rd8 {Protecting the queen and reinforcing the pin along the first rank. Even in the endgame, White will have no good way to untangle, and we will use our passed e-pawn to cause even more problems.} *

