1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 ({Along with} 4. Nf3 {, this is the most popular continuation. White kicks away the knight and occupies more central space.}) 4... Nb6 5. Nf3 ({This is the only feasible alternative to} 5. f4 {and exd6 , and it will likely transpose to the main line since White can hardly keep the central tension up for long.}) 5... Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Nc6 {Developing and applying pressure to White's center.} 8. exd6 Nxd4 {An important intermediate move, grabbing the pawn and hitting the queen.} 9. Qxb7 Qxd6 {Eliminating the pawn and bringing out the queen.} 10. Bd3 Rd8 11. Nc3 Nd7 {The knight has done its job on b6 , and we now maneuver it to a more promising square. We threaten ideas related to ... Nc5 and ... Ne5 .} 12. Ne4 Qb6 13. Qxb6 axb6 {Due to the activity of the knights and the weakness of White's Queenside, we have a powerful initiative. We will follow up with ... Ne5 , and can bring out the dark-squared bishop with ... e6 .} *


