1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 ({Along with} 4. Nf3 {, this is the most popular continuation. White kicks away the knight and occupies more central space.}) 4... Nb6 5. Nf3 ({This is the only feasible alternative to} 5. f4 {and exd6 , and it will likely transpose to the main line since White can hardly keep the central tension up for long.}) 5... Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Nc6 {Developing and applying pressure to White's center.} 8. Be3 {White defends the pawn.} dxe5 9. dxe5 e6 {Fixing the weak pawn on e5 and preparing to develop the bishop.} 10. Nc3 Nd7 {Hitting the pawn with the other knight.} 11. O-O-O {White indirectly defends the e5 -pawn, which is now untouchable since the queen will be lost.} Qe7 {Removing the queen from the pin, renewing the threat of ... Nxe5 , and preparing to castle Queenside.} 12. Nb5 O-O-O {Bringing the king to safety and defending the c7 -pawn. The e5 -pawn is once again under fire.} 13. Nxa7+ Nxa7 14. Bxa7 Nxe5 {The smoke has cleared, and Black's position is perfectly sound. Once the Rooks get traded, the f8 - a3 diagonal will be opened for our bishop, and our knight can find a lovely parking spot on c6 .} *

