1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 ({Along with} 4. Nf3 {, this is the most popular continuation. White kicks away the knight and occupies more central space.}) 4... Nb6 5. exd6 ({The main alternative to this move,} 5. f4 {, is known as The Four Pawns Attack and is examined in its own chapter.}) (5. Nf3 {is the only feasible alternative to f4 and exd6 , and it will likely transpose to the main line since White can hardly keep the central tension up for long.} Bg4 6. exd6 exd6 7. Be2 Be7 8. O-O O-O {will transpose to exd6 exd6 Nf3 Be7 Be2 O-O O-O Bg4 .}) 5... exd6 {White does not have that many developmental setups. Essentially, there are two methods of development: those involving bringing the knight to f3 , and those involving developing the knight to e2 . While there are nominally a lot of options in this position, most of them ultimately transpose into the same type of position once White commits to developing the g1 -knight.} 6. Nf3 {White prioritizes his own Kingside development.} (6. Bd3 {this move has very little independent value, because it is almost always going to transpose to one of the main lines, analyzed through the 6. Nc3 or 6. Nf3 move order.} Be7 {prioritizing our Kingside development and preparing to bring the king to safety.} 7. Ne2 O-O 8. O-O c6 9. Nbc3 Na6 {Transposes to the main line Nc3 Be7 Bd3 O-O Nge2 c6 O-O Na6 .}) 6... Be7 {Our response doesn't change; we also quickly bring out the bishop and tuck our king away to the Kingside.} 7. Be2 (7. Nc3 O-O {transposes to Nc3 Be7} 8. Bd3 {.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O Bg4 {Developing the bishop to its most active spot, and creating the long-term possibility of ... Bxf3 , when the c4 -pawn will hang if White recaptures with the bishop.} 9. Nc3 (9. h3 Bh5 10. Nc3 Nc6 {transposes to Nc3 Nc6 h3 Bh5 .}) 9... Nc6 {Developing the knight and creating the threat of ... Bxf3 and ... Nxc4 , which earlier was impossible because b7 would be hanging.} 10. Be3 {This ignores the threat and leads immediately to a bad position.} Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nxc4 {We have a healthy extra pawn.} *


