1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 ({Along with} 4. Nf3 {, this is the most popular continuation. White kicks away the knight and occupies more central space.}) 4... Nb6 5. exd6 ({The main alternative to this move,} 5. f4 {, is known as the four pawns attack and is examined in its own chapter. Nf3 is the only feasible alternative to f4 and exd6 , and it will likely transpose to the main line since White can hardly keep the central tension up for long. Bg4 exd6 exd6 Be2 Be7 O-O O-O transposes to exd6 exd6 Nf3 Be7 Be2 O-O O-O Bg4 .}) 5... exd6 {White does not have that many developmental setups. Essentially, there are two methods of development: those involving bringing the knight to f3 , and those involving developing the knight to e2 . While there are nominally a lot of options in this position, most of them ultimately transpose into the same type of position once White commits to developing the g1 -knight.} 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Nf3 O-O {Getting the king to safety. This is our response to all of White's seventh-move alternatives.} 8. h3 {White prevents ... Bg4 , but we have a nice alternate development square for our bishop on f5 .} Bf5 9. Be2 Nc6 {Continuing to develop our pieces.} 10. a3 Bf6 11. O-O Re8 {Achieving the perfect setup. We are now ready to carry out the standard central strike ... d5 .} 12. Be3 d5 13. c5 Nc4 {Jumping into the nice c4 -square, and inviting a favorable trade.} 14. Bc1 Be4 {Another standard move, increasing the pressure on the d4 -pawn.} 15. Nxe4 dxe4 {It is very important to recapture with the pawn, counterattacking the f3 -knight.} 16. Bxc4 exf3 17. Qxf3 Qxd4 {Reestablishing material equality with an excellent position.} 18. Qb3 Ne5 {Defending the f7 -pawn with tempo. We can proceed by recapturing on c5 , yielding an excellent position.} *

