1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 ({Along with} 4. Nf3 {, this is the most popular continuation. White kicks away the knight and occupies more central space.}) 4... Nb6 5. exd6 ({The main alternative to this move,} 5. f4 {, is known as the four pawns attack and is examined in its own chapter. Nf3 is the only feasible alternative to f4 and exd6 , and it will likely transpose to the main line since White can hardly keep the central tension up for long. Bg4 exd6 exd6 Be2 Be7 O-O O-O transposes to exd6 exd6 Nf3 Be7 Be2 O-O O-O Bg4 .}) 5... exd6 {White does not have that many developmental setups. Essentially, there are two methods of development: those involving bringing the knight to f3 , and those involving developing the knight to e2 . While there are nominally a lot of options in this position, most of them ultimately transpose into the same type of position once White commits to developing the g1 -knight.} 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Rc1 Bg5 {Initiating a favorable trade of bishops, which softens up White's center and enables us to develop rapid pressure against White's king, which is stuck in the center.} 9. Bxg5 Qxg5 10. Nf3 Re8+ ({White has no good way to cover the check, since Be2 runs into} 10... Qxg2 {.}) *

