1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 ({Along with} 4. Nf3 {, this is the most popular continuation. White kicks away the knight and occupies more central space.}) 4... Nb6 5. exd6 ({The main alternative to this move,} 5. f4 {, is known as the four pawns attack and is examined in its own chapter. Nf3 is the only feasible alternative to f4 and exd6 , and it will likely transpose to the main line since White can hardly keep the central tension up for long. Bg4 exd6 exd6 Be2 Be7 O-O O-O transposes to exd6 exd6 Nf3 Be7 Be2 O-O O-O Bg4 .}) 5... exd6 {White does not have that many developmental setups. Essentially, there are two methods of development: those involving bringing the knight to f3 , and those involving developing the knight to e2 . While there are nominally a lot of options in this position, most of them ultimately transpose into the same type of position once White commits to developing the g1 -knight.} 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Nge2 c6 {This move represents the central idea of the line. We are preparing to stake our claim in the center with ... d5 . As for the knight on b8 , it can join society via a6 and c7 . When White places the Knight on e2 , Black doesn't have a good spot for the bishop because, after ... Bg4 , White will have f3 ! This is why we changed our strategy in this game.} 9. O-O Na6 {Developing the knight, and hinting at ... Nb4 in addition to ... Nc7 .} 10. b3 d5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 {Leaving White with a weak isolated pawn on d4 .} 13. Nf4 {Obviously, we avoid ... Qxd4 due to the discovered check on h7 .} Qd6 14. Bxa6 bxa6 {Note that the damaged Queenside pawn structure does not bother us in the slightest, as it is handsomely compensated by our bishop pair and general piece activity.} 15. Be3 Bf5 {Completing our minor-piece development.} 16. Rc1 Rfe8 {Deploying the Rook to its usual square. We can follow up with ... Bf6 , pressuring the weak pawn on d4 .} *

