1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. dxe5 Bg4 {Developing the bishop to its most active square, and preparing to apply pressure on the weak e5 -pawn.} 6. Bc4 e6 {Securing the knight and opening the long diagonal for the bishop.} 7. O-O Nc6 {Attacking the e5 -pawn.} 8. Bb5 Qd7 {Taking the sting out of the capture on c6 . We are not afraid of self-pinning since White has no way to put pressure on the knight.} 9. c4 Ndb4 {Removing the knight to an even more active square. The potential threat of ... Nc2 forces White to transition to an unpleasant endgame.} 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 11. Nc3 a6 12. Ba4 Kc8 {Unpinning the knight and creating the major threat of ... Bxf3 and ... Nxe5 .} 13. a3 Nd3 14. Bxc6 bxc6 {With the queens off the board, we are not afraid of cosmetically damaging our structure.} 15. Rd1 Nc5 {Obviously, we should refrain from ... Nxe5 since White gets two pieces for a Rook and an ultra-active knight on e5 .} 16. Bg5 Nd7 {The knight has completed its world tour, and triumphantly returns to d7 , where it pressures the e5 -pawn and forces White's bishop into passivity.} 17. Bf4 g5 ({A beautiful thematic shot, separating the bishop from the pawn. Now, Bg3 is met with} 17... h5 {, but the capture on g5 is even worse!}) 18. Bxg5 Bxf3 {Opening the g-file! White's bishop is toast.} 19. gxf3 Rg8 20. Ne4 Be7 21. Kh1 Rxg5 ({It is important to avoid} 21... Bxg5 {due to} 22. Rg1 $1) 22. Nxg5 Bxg5 {Black has two pieces for a Rook, and White's pawn structure is in ruins. He will likely lose the e5 -pawn, leading to a technically winning position for Black.} *


