1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. dxe5 Bg4 {Developing the bishop to its most active square, and preparing to apply pressure on the weak e5 -pawn.} 6. h3 Bxf3 {Trading in order to develop our remaining pieces more quickly and soften up the e5 -square.} 7. Qxf3 e6 {Securing the knight and opening up the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop.} 8. Nc3 c6 {Taking the sting out of the trade on d5 by preparing to recapture first with the queen, and then with the c-pawn to maintain the integrity of our structure.} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Qxd5 cxd5 {White's bishop pair is meaningless, since the knight is no worse than White's light-squared bishop.} 11. Be3 Nd7 {Simultaneously hitting the pawn and preparing to develop the bishop to c5 .} 12. f4 Bc5 13. Bd2 a6 {Hampering the active development of White's bishop.} 14. Be2 h5 {Grabbing space on the Kingside, and preparing to drive the pawn to h4 in order to isolate White's f4 - e5 pawn chain. The endgame is very comfortable for Black.} *

