1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. dxe5 Bg4 {Developing the bishop to its most active square, and preparing to apply pressure on the weak e5 -pawn.} 6. h3 Bxf3 {Trading in order to develop our remaining pieces more quickly and soften up the e5 -square.} 7. Qxf3 e6 {Securing the knight and opening up the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop.} 8. Bc4 Nd7 {As in the 8. Qe4 variation, the knight is developed to d7 to leave open the c6 -square for our c-pawn. Note that Bxd5 runs into the lovely Nxe5 , so White must burn another move to defend the dreadfully-weak e5 -pawn.} 9. Qg3 c6 {Supporting the knight and taking the sting out of Bxd5 .} 10. O-O Qa5 {A powerful move, preparing a double attack against the bishop and e5 -pawn with ... N5b6 .} 11. Bd2 Qc5 {Power chess! This hits the bishop and x-rays the c2 -pawn.} 12. Bb3 Ne7 {Following up on the idea set up by our tenth move, and achieving the secondary aim of retooling the knight to a more stable and active post on f5 .} 13. Bc3 Nf5 14. Qh2 b5 {Preparing to drive out the White bishop with ... b4 .} 15. Nd2 b4 16. Ne4 Qb6 {Retreating the queen and vacating the c5 -square for the knight.} 17. Bd2 Nc5 {Contesting White's active knight.} 18. Rae1 Nxe4 19. Rxe4 Be7 {Completing our minor-piece development. Our lovely knight on f5 and space advantage on the Queenside guarantees great long-term chances.} *

