1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. dxe5 Bg4 {Developing the bishop to its most active square, and preparing to apply pressure on the weak e5 -pawn.} 6. Be2 Nc6 {Now that the bishop has committed to e2 , we do not fear Bb5 and can develop the knight to its most active square.} 7. O-O e6 8. c4 {Pressuring the c4 -pawn, creating the potential threat of ... Bxf3 followed by ... Nxc4 . In positions with the weak White pawn on e5 , the trade of queens is almost always in Black's favor.} Nb6 9. Bf4 {Allowing the queen trade is inaccurate as it allows us to easily apply pressure to e5 .} Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Nd7 {Applying pressure on e5} 11. Nc3 h6 {Preparing to expand on the Kingside with ... g7 - g5 . It is important not to rush ... Bxf3 and ... Ndxe5 , since White will capture on e5 and then ruin our structure with Bxb7 .} 12. h3 g5 {Meeting fire with fire! The exchange of bishops will be squarely in Black's favor, since there will be no way to defend the e5 -pawn.} 13. Be3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Ndxe5 {Now that the bishop has lost contact with the e5 -knight, it is time to collect the harvest.} 15. Bxc6+ Nxc6 16. Nb5 Rc8 {Calmly defending the c7 -pawn.} 17. Bxa7 Bg7 {Completing our development and aiming at the b2 -pawn. White's pieces are discombobulated, and our space advantage, coupled with the more active pieces, grant us an advantage in the endgame.} *


