1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. dxe5 Bg4 {Developing the bishop to its most active square, and preparing to apply pressure on the weak e5 -pawn.} 6. Be2 Nc6 {Now that the bishop has committed to e2 , we do not fear Bb5 and can develop the knight to its most active square.} 7. O-O e6 8. c4 {Pressuring the c4 -pawn, creating the potential threat of ... Bxf3 followed by ... Nxc4 . In positions with the weak White pawn on e5 , the trade of queens is almost always in Black's favor.} Nb6 9. Qc2 Nd7 {This move is effective even with the queens on the board.} 10. Bf4 h6 {An important move, preparing to expand on the Kingside, French Defense-style, with ... g7 - g5 . Eventually, we intend to drop our bishop back to f5 and push the pawn all the way to g4 , isolating the e5 -pawn.} 11. Nc3 Bf5 12. Qc1 g5 {Carrying out the main idea. Note the inclusion of ... Bf5 , which leaves the path completely open for our g-pawn.} 13. Bg3 a6 {A subtle prophylactic move, taking the b5 -square under control. This becomes important in the event of ... Qe7 , which is our response to Rd1 . The knight on c3 is fully restricted by the a6 - and e6 -pawns.} 14. Rd1 Qe7 {Revealing the point of ... a6 .} 15. h3 Bg7 {Completing the minor-piece development and attacking the e5 -pawn.} 16. Qe3 Qc5 {Challenging White's queen.} 17. Nd4 Bxe5 {The complications work out in Black's favor, leaving us with an extra pawn. Note the defensive power of the knight on d7 , which guards both e5 and c5 .} 18. Nxf5 exf5 19. Qxc5 Nxc5 20. Bxe5 Nxe5 {The smoke has cleared, and we are up a pawn with excellently-coordinated knights. We do not fear Rd5 on account of ... Ncd7 , when the knights safely defend each other.} *

