1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Bd3 Nd7 {Immediately challenging White's active knight on e5 .} 7. O-O Nxe5 8. dxe5 g6 {We continue by deploying our dark-squared bishop to the long diagonal, hitting White's e5 -pawn.} 9. Qe2 Bg7 10. a3 O-O {Completing our Kingside development and removing our king to safety.} 11. h3 Qc7 {Mobilizing the queen and hitting the weak pawn on e5 .} 12. Re1 Be6 {This is an excellent square for the bishop: it is sheltered by the e5 -pawn, and does a great job of supporing the knight and exerting pressure on White's Queenside in the event of c4 ... Nb6 .} 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 b5 {Fixing White's Queenside weaknesses and carving out a nice post for our bishop on d5 .} 15. f4 Bd5 {With our previous move, we have taken the sting out of c3 - c4 , and stand very well. We can continue by mobilizing one of our Rooks to d8 , and eventually, carving up White's center with ... f6 .} *


