1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Bd3 Nd7 {Immediately challenging White's active knight on e5 .} 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 {It is important to take with the queen here, in order to possess the ability to directly attack the d4 -pawn in the event of c2 - c4 .} 8. O-O g6 ({As usual, the bishop is deployed on the long diagonal.} 8... e6 {is inferior, since it blocks the potential development of the other bishop.}) 9. c4 Nc7 {This is a great square for the knight, since it can reposition to e6 as well as support the thematic ... b7 - b5 pawn break.} 10. Be3 Bg7 11. Bc2 b5 {Carving out the d5 -square for the knight. White has a very hard time keeping the center in one piece, since 12.b3 will open up the long diagonal and expose White to the incredibly nasty break ... c6 - c5 .} *

