1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Bd3 Nd7 {Immediately challenging White's active knight on e5 .} 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 {It is important to take with the queen here, in order to possess the ability to directly attack the d4 -pawn in the event of c2 - c4 .} 8. O-O g6 ({As usual, the bishop is deployed on the long diagonal.} 8... e6 {is inferior, since it blocks the potential development of the other bishop.}) 9. c3 Bg7 10. Re1 O-O {Completing our Kingside development and shuttling the king to safety.} 11. Nd2 c5 ({We have awaited the moment that White has lost contact with the light-squared bishop to engineer this central break. Now, dxc5 runs into} 11... Nxc3 {, so White has no choice but to accept an isolated pawn or the dissolution of his center.}) 12. Nb3 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Rd8 {Mobilizing the Rook.} 14. Bg5 Bxd4 ({This exchange might seem overly committal, but we will follow up with} 14... Qg4 {, forcing the exchange of queens and minimizing the effect of our Kingside dark-square weaknesses.}) 15. cxd4 Qg4 {Hitting the queen, the bishop, and the d4 -pawn. White must choose between giving up the all-important pawn or acquiescing to the exchange of queens, neither of which constitutes a remotely appealing option.} 16. Qxg4 Bxg4 17. Bc4 Be6 {Our excellent blockading post on d5 gives Black an easy game in the endgame.} *


