1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Bd3 Nd7 {Immediately challenging White's active knight on e5 .} 7. Nf3 N7f6 8. h3 Nb4 {Yet again, this thematic shot comes with great effect. We threaten to seize the bishop pair, thereby garnering an active post for our light-squared bishop on f5 .} 9. Bc4 Bf5 10. Bb3 e6 {Blunting White's bishop and preparing to develop our own.} 11. a3 Na6 12. O-O Bd6 {Deploying the bishop to an active square, and preparing to ferry our king to safety.} 13. c4 O-O 14. Nc3 h6 {Preventing the annoying Bg5 , and taking the sting out of Nh4 , which is now comfortably met with ... Bh7 .} 15. Re1 Nb8 {Re-deploying the knight to d7 , where it will control the important c5 - and e5 -squares. White possesses a minor objective edge to his space advantage and superior central control, but Black has an easy plan connected with the execution of the ... e6 - e5 break.} *

