1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Bd3 Nd7 {Immediately challenging White's active knight on e5 .} 7. Nf3 N7f6 8. O-O Nb4 {The same idea as in the 8.h3 line, temporarily bringing the knight to b4 in order to open up the square f5 for our bishop.} 9. Re1 Bg4 {It is important to prioritize our development even over the bishop pair. Taking on d3 enables White to recapture with the queen, and then ... Bg4 will be met by the nasty knight jump to e5 .} 10. Be2 Bf5 {Now that we have induced the bishop retreat, we remove our own bishop to its optimal post, forcing White to position his knight awkwardly on a3 .} 11. Na3 e6 12. c3 Nbd5 {Moving the knight back to the center.} 13. Qb3 Bxa3 {This move might seem counterintuitive, but it is important to prevent the knight from reaching the e5 -post via c4 .} 14. Qxa3 Qe7 {Slicing away at White's control over the a3 - f8 diagonal.} 15. Qb3 h6 {Preventing the bishop from developing to g5 .} 16. a3 Qc7 {Repositioning the queen in order to open up the retreating e7 -post for the knight.} 17. c4 Ne7 18. Ne5 O-O {Black is slightly worse due to White's bishop pair, but our control over the d5 -square, coupled with the long-term pressure we will exert on the d4 -pawn with ... Rad8 , gives us relatively easy play.} *


