1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Be2 Bf5 {When possible, this is the ideal development square for the bishop.} 7. g4 {A very principled move that we must respond to with great accuracy. White weakens his Kingside, but sends our bishop back to an awkward square. The subsequent lines must be studied and memorized carefully.} Be6 {Preserving the bishop. While e6 is not an ideal square, this is superior to undeveloping the bishop or moving it to d7 , which would block the knight's development.} 8. f4 f6 {Kicking away the centralized knight, and granting our bishop f7 as a potential retreating square.} 9. Nd3 Na6 {It is important to leave the d7 -square for the queen.} 10. O-O g6 {Preparing to undermine White's overextended Kingside pawns with ... h7 - h5 .} 11. Nc3 h5 {It is important not to delay this move, which comes with great effect due to White's not-fully-developed pieces.} 12. gxh5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Qa5 {A lovely lateral developing move, hitting c3 and h5 , and preparing to shuttle the queen to the Kingside.} 14. hxg6 Qf5 {The g-pawn cannot be defended, and Black develops a massive attack against White's exposed king.} 15. Rf2 Qxg6+ 16. Rg2 Qh7 {Stacking up on the h-file. We will involve our bishop with ... Bd5 , and can hide our king on the other side at our convenience.} *

