1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Be2 Bf5 {When possible, this is the ideal development square for the bishop.} 7. g4 {A very principled move that we must respond to with great accuracy. White weakens his Kingside, but sends our bishop back to an awkward square. The subsequent lines must be studied and memorized carefully.} Be6 {Preserving the bishop. While e6 is not an ideal square, this is superior to undeveloping the bishop or moving it to d7 , which would block the knight's development.} 8. f4 f6 {Kicking away the centralized knight, and granting our bishop f7 as a potential retreating square.} 9. Nd3 Na6 {It is important to leave the d7 -square for the queen.} 10. O-O g6 {Preparing to undermine White's overextended Kingside pawns with ... h7 - h5 .} 11. Nc3 h5 {It is important not to delay this move, which comes with great effect due to White's not-fully-developed pieces.} 12. f5 gxf5 13. g5 {White tries to keep the Kingside shut down, while aiming at the h5 -pawn with his queen and bishop. We must respond with great tactical precision and fearlessness.} Qd7 {Ignoring the attack on h5 ! It turns out that the capture, though it comes with check, ultimately helps Black, as it opens up the Kingside and enables us to develop massive threats against White's king.} 14. Bxh5+ Bf7 15. g6 Rg8 {The first of several precise tactical shots, pinning and immobilizing the g-pawn.} 16. Kf2 {In order to maintain a feasible position, White must uncork this incredibly difficult move.} Rxg6 ({The second powerful move, sacrificing the exchange in order to eliminate White's Kingside play. Note that} 16... Bxg6 {will drop an entire Rook due to} 17. Bxg6+ Rxg6 18. Qh5 {.}) 17. Bxg6 Bxg6 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 {Black's compensation is based on three factors:   1) We have a pawn for the exchange.   2) We possess the bishop pair and great light square control.   3) Our king will be much safer than its counterpart once it castles Queenside.} 19. Nf4 Qd6 {Keeping the queen maximally active and tactically defending the bishop.} 20. Nxg6 Qxh2+ 21. Ke3 Bh6+ 22. Kd3 Nc5+ {The king is hunted down with a series of lovely tactical shots. The knight is untouchable due to long castling, which will pick up White's queen.} *

