   3) Our king will be much safer than its counterpart once it castles Queenside.} 19. Nf4 Qd6 {Keeping the queen maximally active and tactically defending the bishop.} 20. Qd3 Nb4 {Hitting the queen and involving the knight in the attack.} 21. Qh3 Bf7 {Now that White has protected the h2 -pawn, the bishop must be retreated to safety. Note that the d4 -pawn is now hanging, so White must waste a tempo and allow our knight to participate even more fully in the attack.} 22. c3 Nc2 23. Rb1 Qd7 {Before tucking away our king, we must ensure that the f5 -pawn is protected.} 24. Qd3 O-O-O {Sacrificing the knight in order to tuck away the king and prepare to reignite the flames of attack with a central pawn break.} 25. Qxc2 e5 {Black's compensation for the Rook consists in our massive pawn center, our excellently coordinated pieces, and White's wide-open king. We can proceed by continuing to advance our phalanx with ... f4 , opening up a pathway to h3 for our queen.} *

