1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Be2 Bf5 {When possible, this is the ideal development square for the bishop.} 7. g4 {A very principled move that we must respond to with great accuracy. White weakens his Kingside, but sends our bishop back to an awkward square. The subsequent lines must be studied and memorized carefully.} Be6 {Preserving the bishop. While e6 is not an ideal square, this is superior to undeveloping the bishop or moving it to d7 , which would block the knight's development.} 8. c4 Nb6 9. b3 {This is too slow, and enables us to kick away the knight with great effect.} f6 {White cannot avoid the loss of either the g4 - or d4 -pawn, both of which are essential to the integrity of White's position.} 10. Nd3 Qxd4 11. Bb2 Qd7 {This is better than ... Qd8 , as it enables us to more quickly hide away the king.} 12. a4 Na6 {As is so typical in this line, we develop the knight to a6 , from where it can join the game more directly through b4 or c5 .} 13. a5 Nc8 14. Nc3 h5 {Another thematic shot, striking at the g4 -pawn in order to generate a better post for our bishop and enable us to complete our Kingside development.} 15. gxh5 Bf5 16. Na4 e5 {Driving a stake through the center, blunting White's dark-squared bishop and opening up a diagonal for our own.} 17. Qd2 Nd6 {Centralizing the knight.} 18. O-O-O Qe7 {It is important to remove the queen from the Rook's x-ray, taking the sting out of Nxe5 -related ideas.} 19. Qe3 g6 {And a lovely tactical shot to finish it off, hitting the h5 -pawn and threatening ... Bh6 . White's position is on the verge of collapse, since Kb1 walks right into the pin exerted by our light-squared bishop.} *

