1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Be2 Bf5 {When possible, this is the ideal development square for the bishop.} 7. g4 {A very principled move that we must respond to with great accuracy. White weakens his Kingside, but sends our bishop back to an awkward square. The subsequent lines must be studied and memorized carefully.} Be6 {Preserving the bishop. While e6 is not an ideal square, this is superior to undeveloping the bishop or moving it to d7 , which would block the knight's development.} 8. c4 Nb6 9. c5 {This tempting move is harmless, as it yields us the lovely outpost on d5 .} Nd5 10. f4 g6 {Slowing down the progress of White's Kingside pawns, and preparing to fianchetto the bishop.} 11. O-O Qc8 {It is critical to prevent f4 - f5 at all costs.} 12. Nc3 Nd7 {We now proceed to smoke out the knight from e5 , enabling us to develop more freely.} 13. Bf3 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nxc3 {Releasing the central tension and permanently crippling White's Queenside pawn structure.} 15. bxc3 Bg7 {Finishing up our Kingside development, and preparing to remove our king to safety.} 16. Qe2 O-O {White's damaged pawn structure, coupled with the overextended nature of White's Kingside pawns, guarantees us excellent play. We can follow up by undermining Whtie's pawn chain with ... f7 - f6 , generating exciting prospects in the center and on the Kingside.} *

