1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 {5...c6 is a good supportive move. Black will avoid all potential double attacks and pins from the Queen and Bishop.} 6. Be2 Bf5 {When possible, this is the ideal development square for the bishop.} 7. O-O Nd7 {Natural and strong, developing our knight and smoking out White's knight from the center.} 8. Nf3 e6 9. c4 N5f6 {In this particular instance, this move is preferrable to ... Nb4 . We need the knight on the Kingside in order to make the ... e6 - e5 break easier to achieve later on.} 10. Bf4 Be7 11. Nc3 O-O {Completing our Kingside development.} 12. h3 h6 {Making luft for the bishop, taking the sting out of Nh4 .} 13. Qb3 Qb6 {This is the typical way of meeting Qb3 .} 14. Rfd1 Rfd8 {Centralizing the Rook.} 15. Qxb6 axb6 {Of course, we recapture with the pawn in order to open up prospects for our queen's Rook.} 16. a3 Ne4 {Contesting the center with the typical knight sally. Our position is solid and our pieces are well-coordinated.} *

