 queen with ... Qxd5 .} 26. Bxf6 Nf3+ {Throwing in an important check to set up the threat of a discovered check after ... Qxd5 .} 27. Kg2 Qxd5 28. Bxc3 Ne1+ 29. Kh3 {It appears that White has finally escaped our clutches, since the tempting Qg2+ enables the king to escape, but to our aid comes an incredible tactical shot:} Rb4 {Luring the queen to a vulnerable spot. Of course, the bishop cannot capture due to the checkmate on h5 .} 30. Qxb4 Qg2+ 31. Kh4 Qxh2+ 32. Kg4 Qh5+ {Pursuing the king with a series of active checks.} 33. Kf4 Qf5+ 34. Ke3 Qd3+ {Forcing perpetual check with ... Qf5 + and ... Qd3 +.} ({Note that} 34... Nc2+ {followed by ... Nxb4 gives White way too many pieces for the queen.}) *

