1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 {This is the most principled continuation for White.} dxe5 6. fxe5 Bf5 ({In my experience, this move complicates the position for white. It is less common than} 6... Nc6 {, and faces White with immediate practical difficulties. The main point is to delay ... Nc6 , to have the option of challenging White's center with ... c5 later on.}) 7. Nc3 e6 8. Be3 Bb4 {This presents White with a huge menu of options, complicating his experience. Based on my experience, White has a very hard time finding a proper arrangement of pieces, and it is easy to commit a serious error as early as the next move.} 9. Nf3 c5 {The typical move, shattering White's center.} 10. Be2 O-O {Adhering to our general strategy of keeping the tension, and giving White the possibility of entering a nearly losing endgame after dxc5 (much like in the 10. dxc5 variation ).} 11. O-O cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bg6 {Obviously, we have to keep our light-squared bishop.} 13. Qb3 Bc5 {Pinning and attacking the knight.} 14. Rad1 Qc7 {Moving the queen away from the pin and attacking e5 .} 15. Kh1 {A big brain move: the pawn on e5 is now poisoned due to Bf4 , when Black loses material since ... Bxd4 no longer comes with check.} a6 {Preventing the knight from jumping to b5 .} 16. Bf4 Rd8 {Hitting the knight, so we can develop our own knight to c6 .} 17. Nf3 Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Nc6 {We threaten to win the queen with ... Na5 , and White's flimsy pawn structure gives us a stable advantage.} *

