1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 {This is the most principled continuation for White.} dxe5 6. fxe5 Bf5 ({In my experience, this move complicates the position for white. It is less common than} 6... Nc6 {, and faces White with immediate practical difficulties. The main point is to delay ... Nc6 , to have the option of challenging White's center with ... c5 later on.}) 7. Nc3 e6 8. Nf3 {The most popular, and most logical, response.} Bb4 {This line leads to an extremely sharp position in which White will face serious practical problems with his center. In my experience, even the strongest players are unable to find the best solutions.} 9. Bd3 (9. Be3 {transposes to Be3 Bb4 Nf3 .}) 9... c5 10. d5 Bxc3+ {Just as in the 10. Bg5 line, it is important to damage White's pawn structure to create additional targets on the Queenside and in the center.} 11. bxc3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 exd5 {Grabbing material!} 13. O-O dxc4 14. Qf5 Qd3 {Using the outpost to mobilize our queen and take the sting out of the f-file pressure.} 15. Qg4 Qg6 {The queen joins the defense, keeping White away from Black's Kingside weaknesses. Note that the knight on b6 plays a vital role, defending the c8 -square.} *

