1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 {This is the most principled continuation for White.} dxe5 6. fxe5 Bf5 ({In my experience, this move complicates the position for white. It is less common than} 6... Nc6 {, and faces White with immediate practical difficulties. The main point is to delay ... Nc6 , to have the option of challenging White's center with ... c5 later on.}) 7. Nc3 e6 8. Nf3 {The most popular, and most logical, response.} Bb4 {This line leads to an extremely sharp position in which White will face serious practical problems with his center. In my experience, even the strongest players are unable to find the best solutions.} 9. Bd3 (9. Be3 {transposes to Be3 Bb4 Nf3 .}) 9... c5 10. d5 Bxc3+ {Just as in the 10. Bg5 line, it is important to damage White's pawn structure to create additional targets on the Queenside and in the center.} 11. bxc3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 exd5 {Grabbing material!} 13. O-O dxc4 14. Qxd8+ Kxd8 15. Ng5 Re8 {The f7 -pawn cannot be defended, but we escape the fork and pressure the e5 -pawn.} 16. Nxh7 {A non-obvious move, leaving the f7 -pawn for the Rook. Unfortunately, Re7 runs into Bg5 , so we must give up the f-pawn as well.} N8d7 17. Rxf7 Nd5 18. Rxg7 Rxe5 {White is objectively better, but the position remains highly unbalanced and Black possesses excellent practical chances connected to the weak pawn on c3 and our potential to activate the other Rook.} *

