1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 {This is the most principled continuation for White.} dxe5 6. fxe5 Bf5 ({In my experience, this move complicates the position for white. It is less common than} 6... Nc6 {, and faces White with immediate practical difficulties. The main point is to delay ... Nc6 , to have the option of challenging White's center with ... c5 later on.}) 7. Nc3 e6 8. Nf3 {The most popular, and most logical, response.} Bb4 {This line leads to an extremely sharp position in which White will face serious practical problems with his center. In my experience, even the strongest players are unable to find the best solutions.} 9. Bd3 (9. Be3 {transposes to Be3 Bb4 Nf3 .}) 9... c5 10. Bxf5 {This is the most popular reaction, but it is not the strongest.} cxd4 {A crucial intermediate move, shattering White's center before recapturing the bishop.} 11. Bg5 Qc7 {Here, the queen is placed better than on d7 : it attacks c4 and pressures e5 .} 12. Qxd4 exf5 13. O-O-O O-O {Not forgetting about the safety of our king!} 14. b3 {White must defend the pawn on c4 .} Nc6 {Developing with tempo.} 15. Nb5 {Far from obvious, this move counterattacks Black's queen. There is no other way to keep everything protected.} Qc8 {Protecting the pawn on f5 for the future, and keeping the x-ray against White's king.} 16. Qf4 Nd7 {Indirect defense against Qxf5 , which now runs into ... Ndxe5 .} 17. Nd6 Bxd6 18. exd6 f6 {Attacking the bishop and preventing the nasty idea of Be7 .} 19. Bh4 Nc5 {Bringing out the knight to a more active post, as well as defending the f5 -pawn with our queen.} 20. Rhe1 Qd7 {Blockading the d-pawn and connecting the Rooks.} 21. Nd4 Nb4 {Yet again, our knights dominate! We threaten both the family fork on d3 as well as the a2 -pawn. White is faced with tremendous practical difficulties.} *

