1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Bc4 {Not the best sideline, since it allows the knight to step back to b6 with tempo. White's idea is distinct from the main lines, in the sense that he does not attempt to dominate the center with pawns. As a result, Black obtains a very comfortable game.} Nb6 4. Bb3 d5 {Controling the center and preparing ... Bf5 , leading to a French-Advance-type setup with the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 5. d4 Bf5 {Bringing the bishop outside the pawn chain.} 6. Ne2 e6 {Opening the bishop and preparing ... c5 .} 7. O-O c5 {Attacking the center from the flank. This pawn advance is very typical in this type of pawn structure.} 8. c3 Be7 {Developing the bishop and preparing to castle.} 9. Ng3 {An alternate plan that is associated with the rapid march of the f-pawn. Black must react accurately.} Bg6 10. f4 Nc6 {Not hurrying to commit our king to the Kingside.} 11. f5 Bxf5 12. Nxf5 exf5 13. Rxf5 Qc8 {An important insertion, attacking the Rook and indirectly hitting the d4 -pawn (due to the hanging bishop on c1 and the possibility of ... Bc5 ).} 14. Bc2 cxd4 15. cxd4 Nxd4 {The knight is untouchable due to ... Bc5 . White's position collapses.} *

