1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Bc4 {Not the best sideline, since it allows the knight to step back to b6 with tempo. White's idea is distinct from the main lines, in the sense that he does not attempt to dominate the center with pawns. As a result, Black obtains a very comfortable game.} Nb6 4. Bb3 d5 {Controling the center and preparing ... Bf5 , leading to a French-Advance-type setup with the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 5. exd6 Qxd6 {A rather atypical recapture in the Alekhine. The point is to keep our c and e-pawns on their initial squares, to have the possibility of contesting the center with .. .c5 or ... e5 . Furthermore, the queen is safely positioned on d6 , and cannot be targeted.} 6. Qf3 {A typical "blitz move", seemingly preventing the development of Black's bishop. But we ignore the threat on b7 and develop it anyway!} Be6 7. Qxb7 {It turns out that this pawn is poisoned!} Nc6 {Threatening the beautiful ... Bc8 , trapping White's queen. White is forced to burn more tempi on evacuating the queen, when his lack of development becomes critical.} 8. Bxe6 Qxe6+ 9. Kf1 Qc4+ {Forking the king and the c2 -pawn.} 10. Ne2 Rb8 {Suddenly, we switch back to attacking White's queen, which will get trapped.} 11. Qxc7 e5 {Blocking the queen's evacuation route to g3 .} 12. Na3 Qe6 {With a series of ultra-precise moves, we have locked the White queen in the dungeon.} 13. Nb5 Na8 {It is always hard to make retreating moves, but not when they trap the queen! Of course, we should not take the queen immediately, since White will recapture with a fork. Instead, we first eliminate the knight with ... Rxb5 or ... a6 .} *

