1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. a4 {A rare system that is not particularly promising. The inclusion of a4 and ... a5 will favor Black, since we will secure a nice outpost on b4 .} a5 5. c5 Nd5 6. Bc4 Nb4 7. Nf3 d5 {Once again, this active move is the only way to ensure rapid development.} 8. cxd6 exd6 {Recapturing with the e-pawn to open up a nice developing square for our DSB.} 9. O-O d5 {Fixing the center and knocking the bishop off of the diagonal.} 10. Be2 Bf5 {Developing the bishop to its most active post and controlling c2 .} 11. d4 Nc2 {Time to win some material!} 12. Ra2 Nc6 {Suddenly, the Rook is entrapped - White has no truly satisfactory answer to the massive threat of ... N6b4 , trapping the Rook .} 13. b3 N2b4 14. Rb2 Be7 {With the aid of the ... Nd4 - c2 - b4 maneuver, we have ensured complete domination over key squares on the Queenside. White, on the other hand, is still spinning his wheels.} 15. Nc3 Qd7 {Our coordination is perfect, and Black's position is easier to play.} *

