1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. a4 {A rare system that is not particularly promising. The inclusion of a4 and ... a5 will favor Black, since we will secure a nice outpost on b4 .} a5 5. d4 d6 {Of course, we do not miss the moment to challenge White in the center.} 6. exd6 exd6 {Once again, we recapture with the e-pawn as we do in the main line. In fact, we will see this exact position without the inclusion of a4 and ... a5 in the main line. Clearly, this inclusion can only favor Black.} 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Nf3 Nc6 {Continuing our development naturally. Of course, in response to d4 - d5 , we can always jump into the outpost on b4 .} 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Re8 {Occupying the open file and retaining maximum flexibility with respect to the development of our light-squared bishop.} 11. h3 Bf5 12. d5 Nb4 {There's that outpost!} 13. Nd4 Bd7 {Retreating the bishop in order to maintain control of key light squares on the Queenside.} 14. Be3 Bg5 {Preparing to trade off the dark-squared bishop, which keeps White's position stable.} 15. Qd2 Rxe3 {A very thematic exchange sacrifice, straight out of Petrosian's game! The incredibly weak dark squares, coupled with the monster knight on b4 , give us fantastic compensation.} 16. fxe3 Qe7 17. Rf3 Re8 {Increasing the attack on e3 . White's position is very unenviable.} *

