1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 {White continues to push the knight around, but in so doing creates a major weakness on d5 . We will occupy that square with our knight, and proceed to keep our knight protected with our pawns.} Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. d4 (6. Nc3 {will transpose to} Nxc3 {e6 Bc4 .}) 6... b6 {One of the only times when we undermine the c-pawn using our b-pawn and not our d-pawn. The point is to open up the a-file for our Rook and pave the way for the development of the light-squared bishop to a6 , engineering a favorable trade.} 7. cxb6 axb6 8. Ne2 Bb4+ {Developing with check. We are happy to trade dark-squared bishops.} 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Ne7 {Moving away the knight to avoid doubling the pawns.} 11. Nbc3 O-O 12. O-O d5 {Changing our strategy based on White's mode of development. This move decisively grabs control of the center.} 13. exd6 Qxd6 14. Ne4 Qd8 {It may seem that our position is cramped, but through our subtle positional maneuvers, we have created a long-term weakness on d4 , and our prospects for development are excellent. White cannot exploit his temporary lead in development!} 15. Rfd1 Ba6 {Trading off the bishops and increasing our control over d5 . Our pawn structure is superior, and Black's position is very easy to play.} *

