1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 {White continues to push the knight around, but in so doing creates a major weakness on d5 . We will occupy that square with our knight, and proceed to keep our knight protected with our pawns.} Nd5 5. d4 d6 {As usual, we undo the gordion's knight in the center.} 6. cxd6 exd6 7. Nf3 dxe5 {Releasing the tension in the center and opening up better prospects for our dark-squared bishop.} 8. dxe5 Be7 9. Nc3 Nxc3 {As usual, the endgame works in our favor, since White will deal with long-term pawn weaknesses on the Queenside.} 10. Qxd8+ Bxd8 11. bxc3 {Do not be fooled by the outward passivity of our pieces: we will develop quickly and effectively, and White obviously has no way to exploit his temporary development advantage.} Nc6 12. Bc4 Na5 {A nice lateral shot, forcing the bishop onto a more passive square.} 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Re8 15. Re1 Be6 {Objectively, the position is equal, but I would take Black any day. It is practically (our moves are easier to find!) very difficult to play with two long-term isolanis on the Queenside.} *

