1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 {White continues to push the knight around, but in so doing creates a major weakness on d5 . We will occupy that square with our knight, and proceed to keep our knight protected with our pawns.} Nd5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Bc4 Nxc3 7. dxc3 Nc6 8. Bf4 Bxc5 9. Qg4 g5 {An incredible idea, sacrificing the pawn in order to lure White's bishop onto the g-file.} ({h4 remember ...g5 is not our main idea, so in this case, we can simply play} 9... Qe7 $1 {And then we have 10… f6 with a much better position.}) 10. Bxg5 Rg8 {Therein lies the rub! We counter-pin the bishop, forcing a favorable exchange of queens.} 11. h4 h6 {Forcing the bishop off of g5 .} 12. Bxd8 Rxg4 {Both of White's bishop, as well as the g2 -pawn, are hanging! White is able to save the bishops, but not the integrity of his Kingside.} 13. Be2 Rxg2 14. Bxc7 b5 {Another powerful move, expanding on the Queenside and preparing to complete our development by fianchettoing the bishop.} 15. Bxb5 Bb7 16. Nh3 Rg4 {White's position collapses due to the threats along the long diagonal as well as ... Rxh4 .} *

