1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 {White continues to push the knight around, but in so doing creates a major weakness on d5 . We will occupy that square with our knight, and proceed to keep our knight protected with our pawns.} Nd5 5. Nc3 e6 6. d4 d6 {As is so typical in this variation, we strike the c5 and e5 -pawns at once, leading to a favorable liquidation.} 7. cxd6 cxd6 8. Nf3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 {Reaching the hanging pawn structure, We proceed to quickly and efficiently coordinate our pieces while applying pressure on the c3 -pawn.} Qc7 {Hitting the pawn and forcing White to defend it passively.} 10. Bd2 Nd7 {The knight is developed to d7 , and not c6 , in order to leave open the long diagonal for the light-squared bishop.} 11. Bd3 dxe5 12. O-O Bd6 {As is standard in this line, we refrain from capturing the pawn on d4 , which would enable White to open up the c-file and quickly knock the queen off of the c7 -square. Instead, we prioritze development.} 13. Re1 O-O 14. Qe2 Rd8 {Indirectly defending the e5 -pawn due to the eventual threat against White's bishop.} 15. Bg5 f6 {Active defense!} 16. Bh4 exd4 17. Qxe6+ Kh8 18. Qe4 Nf8 {A powerful defensive move, securing the h7 -pawn and opening up better prospects for our light-squared bishop.} 19. cxd4 Be6 20. Bg3 Qf7 {White struggles with a long-term weakness on d4 . Our last move increases our control of the square in front of the isolated pawn, an important strategy in ensuring that the pawn remains immobile and easily attackable. We can entrench a bishop on d5 .} *

